          "$type": "text",
          "text": "# James's Return-to-Running Plan\n\nWelcome back, James. Getting back on your feet after plantar fasciitis takes real patience, and the fact that you've worked with a physio and are approaching this thoughtfully says a lot about how seriously you take your running. Let's build this carefully and sustainably.\n\n---\n\n## First, a Few Things Worth Naming\n\nBefore we dive in, I want to be transparent about how I've thought through your situation:\n\n**Your physio's guidance takes priority over everything in this plan.** You've been cleared for 20-minute easy runs with walking breaks if any foot pain arises. That's the ceiling we're working within — not a floor to push past.\n\nYour pre-injury 10K pace of 4:24/km (44:00) tells me you have real fitness to return to. But fitness built before an injury isn't fully available yet — your tendons and connective tissue need time to catch up to where your cardiovascular system wants to go. We'll honor both.\n\n---\n\n## How This Plan Is Built\n\n**3 days per week** | **Max 20 min/run** | **Easy pace only: 5:25–6:12/km** | **6 weeks**\n\nThe structure is simple on purpose:\n- **Weeks 1–2:** Consolidate what you've already been doing. Build the habit and feel out the foot.\n- **Weeks 3–4:** Gently extend duration toward the 20-minute cap.\n- **Week 5:** Deload — pull back volume intentionally so your body can absorb the work.\n- **Week 6:** Reassess and prepare for the next phase.\n\nNo speed work. No tempo. No intervals. Your physio has been clear, and the physiology backs it up — plantar fascia needs consistent, low-stress loading to remodel, not intensity spikes.\n\n---\n\n## The Plan\n\n### Week 1 (March 23–29) — *Establish the Pattern*\n*Target: ~9 km | 3 runs*\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Tuesday** | Easy Run | 15 min @ 5:25–6:12/km. Walk break at any foot discomfort. |\n| **Thursday** | Easy Run | 15 min @ 5:25–6:12/km. Focus on relaxed form. |\n| **Saturday** | Long Run | 18 min @ 5:25–6:12/km. Treat the extra 3 min as exploration, not effort. |\n\n> **Why this volume?** You ran 8.5 km the week of March 9 and dropped to 6.1 km last week. We're consolidating — not jumping forward. Consistency matters more than mileage right now.\n\n---\n\n### Week 2 (March 30 – April 5) — *Consolidate*\n*Target: ~9.5 km | 3 runs*\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Tuesday** | Easy Run | 15 min @ easy pace. |\n| **Thursday** | Easy Run | 16 min @ easy pace. |\n| **Saturday** | Long Run | 20 min @ easy pace. First time hitting the full cap — stay controlled. |\n\n> **Foot check-in protocol:** Rate your foot discomfort on a 0–10 scale before and after each run this week. If you're seeing anything above a 2/10 *after* a run, that's worth noting — and worth discussing with your physio before Week 3.\n\n---\n\n### Week 3 (April 6–12) — *Build Gently*\n*Target: ~11 km | 3 runs*\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Tuesday** | Easy Run | 18 min @ easy pace. |\n| **Thursday** | Easy Run | 18 min @ easy pace. |\n| **Saturday** | Long Run | 20 min @ easy pace. |\n\n> **Note on the 10% rule:** This week steps up from ~9.5 km to ~11 km — just under 16%. That's a deliberate choice given your low base and the conservative 20-minute cap. If your foot is giving you any feedback, we pull this back to match Week 2.\n\n---\n\n### Week 4 (April 13–19) — *Fill the Cap*\n*Target: ~12 km | 3 runs*\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Tuesday** | Easy Run | 20 min @ easy pace. |\n| **Thursday** | Easy Run | 20 min @ easy pace. |\n| **Saturday** | Long Run | 20 min @ easy pace. |\n\n> You're now running three full 20-minute sessions per week — exactly what your physio has cleared. This is the ceiling until you get the green light to progress. Hold here and let your body consolidate.\n\n---\n\n### Week 5 (April 20–26) — *Deload Week*\n*Target: ~8 km | 3 runs*\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Tuesday** | Easy Run | 15 min @ easy pace. |\n| **Thursday** | Easy Run | 15 min @ easy pace. |\n| **Saturday** | Easy Run | 20 min @ easy pace. |\n\n> **Why pull back now?** This isn't a step backward — it's where adaptation actually happens. Deload weeks allow your plantar fascia, tendons, and supporting structures to consolidate the load you've placed on them over the previous four weeks. Runners who skip deloads often end up forced into a longer one. Think of this as a deposit in the bank.\n\n---\n\n### Week 6 (April 27 – May 3) — *Reassess*\n*Target: ~10 km | 3 runs*\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Tuesday** | Easy Run | 18 min @ easy pace. |\n| **Thursday** | Easy Run | 18 min @ easy pace. |\n| **Saturday** | Easy Run | 20 min @ easy pace. |\n\n> **End-of-plan checkpoint:** At the end of this week, you'll want to check back in with your physio. The questions to bring: *Can I extend beyond 20 minutes? Am I cleared for any structured progression?* Based on that conversation, we can map out Phase 2 — which is where we start building toward your pre-injury fitness and, eventually, race goals.\n\n---\n\n## Important Guardrails for the Whole Plan\n\n**Walking breaks are not a failure.** They're a tool. If your foot speaks up during a run — even a 1–2/10 discomfort — shift to walking. Complete the time, not the running. The goal is cumulative stress on the foot, managed carefully.\n\n**All running is easy pace.** That's 5:25–6:12/km. If it feels too slow, that's usually the right sign. Easy running builds aerobic base, protects healing tissue, and is genuinely where most long-term running fitness comes from.\n\n**No speed work until your physio clears it.** This is non-negotiable from a healing standpoint — high-intensity loading on a recovering plantar fascia is one of the most common ways runners re-injure.\n\n---\n\n## A Note on What Comes Next\n\nYou have a genuine 44-minute 10K in your history. That fitness doesn't disappear — it becomes the target. Once you're through this return phase and fully cleared, we can build a structured program to get you back to that level and beyond.\n\nThe path back is longer than we'd like, but it's real.\n\n---\n\n**One question to get us started:** How has the foot been feeling on your recent runs — any particular point in the run where it tends to flare up, or is it more of a morning stiffness situation? That'll help me fine-tune how we approach the early weeks."
        }
      ],
